Information control formed the third major strand of the week. The Pentagon, under Hegseth, issued new rules requiring journalists to sign pledges not to gather or report \'93unauthorized\'94 information, even if unclassified, on pain of losing their press credentials. Reporters\'92 movements inside the building were restricted to specific areas, and escorts became mandatory for broader access. The memo emphasized that all information must be approved for public release, effectively turning the press gallery into a space for managed messaging rather than independent scrutiny. Free press advocates called it an assault on First Amendment protections, but the policy went into effect. The chill was immediate.\
