Outside the Pentagon, the Federal Communications Commission, led by a loyalist chair, threatened to revoke the broadcast licenses of ABC stations after Jimmy Kimmel criticized the administration\'92s response to the killing of Charlie Kirk. ABC suspended Kimmel\'92s show under that pressure, prompting public backlash, boycotts, and protests. After \'93days of thoughtful conversations\'94 with the host, Disney reinstated the program, but major station groups Sinclair and Nexstar refused to air it on their ABC affiliates. The president then attacked ABC for allowing Kimmel back on the air, calling the show an illegal campaign contribution to Democrats and hinting at further action. The episode showed how regulatory threats, corporate caution, and ownership concentration could combine to narrow the space for critical voices, even when formal censorship was absent. The lesson for other outlets was obvious.\
\
The administration also moved to constrict the flow of inconvenient data. The Bureau of Labor Statistics postponed its annual consumer expenditures report, a key tool for understanding inflation, shortly after the president fired its commissioner following disappointing job numbers. The Department of Agriculture canceled its long-running national food insecurity survey and its annual report on household food security, dismissing them as \'93redundant, costly, politicized and extraneous,\'94 despite last year\'92s finding that 18 million households faced food insecurity. These cancellations came as the USDA froze more than $10 million in food assistance funding for Kansas because the governor refused to hand over personal information on beneficiaries and applicants. Together, the actions reduced public visibility into economic hardship while using federal aid as leverage against a noncompliant state. Data and dollars were both turned into tools.\
\
Even the custodians of historical record were drawn into the struggle. A branch of the National Archives released nearly unredacted military records of Representative Mikie Sherrill to an ally of her Republican opponent in the New Jersey governor\'92s race, including sensitive personal information. The release appeared to violate the Privacy Act and raised the specter of archival processes being used for electoral gain. At the same time, the Archives invited public comment on proposed records schedules, a routine but important step in deciding which federal documents are preserved or destroyed. The contrast between the improper disclosure and the formal process underscored how much depends on the integrity of those who manage the nation\'92s memory. Memory itself was becoming contested ground.\
\
The week\'92s economic and foreign policy moves reinforced the sense that governance and crony networks were becoming hard to distinguish. The State Department announced plans to redirect $1.8 billion in foreign aid toward \'93America First\'94 projects, moving away from traditional goals of promoting democracy and health, and drawing criticism from congressional leaders who saw an attempt to bypass funding laws. Treasury and other agencies prepared a $20 billion aid package for Argentina\'92s right-wing president, a political ally, outside the usual appropriations process. The Treasury also sanctioned the wife of a Brazilian Supreme Court justice who had overseen the prosecution of Jair Bolsonaro, prompting Brazil to accuse the United States of undue interference. At home, the president imposed new tariffs of up to 100 percent on pharmaceuticals and high rates on furniture and heavy trucks, despite prior court rulings limiting his tariff powers, and announced a plan to use tariff revenue to bail out farmers harmed by his trade policies. Meanwhile, Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem expedited $11 million in disaster aid for a historic pier in Naples, Florida, after intervention by a political donor. In each case, economic tools\'97aid, sanctions, tariffs, disaster funds\'97were deployed in ways that aligned closely with ideological allies and donors. Policy and patronage blurred.\
\
Immigration and civil rights policy continued to stratify citizenship. Beyond the ICE funding surge and detention patterns, the administration announced a $100,000 fee for companies employing H-1B visa holders and proposed overhauling the H-1B lottery to favor higher-paid applicants, tilting skilled immigration toward wealthier employers and workers. HUD\'92s rollback of fair housing enforcement, combined with the withholding of $65 million in magnet school grants from districts that refused to change policies for trans and nonbinary students, signaled that civil rights protections for minorities and LGBTQ students were being treated as negotiable. In California, officials investigated the death of Ismael Ayala-Uribe, a Mexican man who died after surgery while in ICE custody, and senators demanded information on ICE detainee deaths more broadly. Lawsuits, such as a $50 million claim by a Los Angeles car wash owner over an ICE raid, and a habeas petition by Rodney Taylor, a double amputee held in detention despite extensive medical needs, sought to force accountability through the courts. These efforts showed that rights were still being asserted, but always against a rising tide. The hierarchy of whose rights counted grew sharper.\
